WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Coach: Hi Maria, thanks for meeting with me today. What's on your mind?

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Maria: Hi Sarah. Thanks for making time for me. I need to talk to a teacher tomorrow about their curriculum implementation, and it's a bit of a sensitive situation.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Coach: I see. You're anticipating a potentially difficult conversation. Can you tell me a little more about what's making you feel apprehensive?

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Maria:  Well, this teacher isn't fully implementing the new curriculum, and it's impacting student learning.  But they're a veteran teacher, and I'm worried they might get defensive or feel like I'm questioning their judgment.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Coach:  That's understandable. It's important to address the issue while also maintaining a positive and supportive relationship with the teacher. What have you considered doing so far?

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Maria:  Honestly, I've been putting off this conversation because I'm not sure how to approach it. I don't want to come across as critical or make them feel like I'm not valuing their experience.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Coach: It sounds like you're really mindful of the teacher's feelings and want to approach this in a way that's respectful and constructive.  What do you think would be the ideal outcome of this conversation?

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:40.000
Maria:  Ideally, I'd like the teacher to understand the importance of fully implementing the curriculum and to be willing to make the necessary changes. But I also want them to feel heard and respected.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Coach:  Those are great goals, Maria. It sounds like you're prioritizing both the students' needs and the teacher's well-being.  Have you thought about any specific strategies for achieving those goals?

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Maria:  Not really.  I've been so focused on the potential challenges that I haven't had a chance to think about solutions.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Coach:  That's okay. We can brainstorm some strategies together.  One effective technique for delivering feedback is to use "I" statements to frame your concerns.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:40.000
Maria:  Can you give me an example of what you mean?

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Coach:  Instead of saying "You're not implementing the curriculum correctly," you could say, "I'm concerned that students might not be getting the full benefit of the curriculum," or "I've noticed that some key components of the curriculum are being omitted."

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Maria:  That's a good idea.  It feels less accusatory and more collaborative.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:25.000
Coach:  Exactly.  It helps to soften the feedback and make it more about your observations and concerns.  And it's important to focus on the impact on student learning.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Maria:  So, I could say something like, "I'm concerned that students aren't mastering the key concepts because some of the activities designed to reinforce those concepts are being skipped."

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:50.000
Coach:  Exactly.  That connects the issue to the bigger picture and emphasizes why it's important to address it.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Maria:  Okay, that's helpful.  What else can I do to make this conversation more productive?

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:20.000
Coach:  Start by acknowledging the teacher's experience and expertise.  Let them know that you value their perspective and appreciate their dedication to their students.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Maria:  That's a good point.  I don't want them to feel like I'm discounting their years of experience or their commitment to teaching.  Maybe I could start by saying something like, "I know you've been a dedicated teacher for many years, and I respect your experience and expertise."

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Coach:  That's a great start, Maria.  You're setting a positive tone and showing that you value their contributions.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Maria:  And then I could transition into expressing my concerns about the curriculum implementation.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Coach:  Exactly.  And remember to be specific in your feedback.  Instead of saying "You're not following the curriculum," provide concrete examples of what you've observed.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Maria:  Like, "I noticed that you skipped this activity in the unit plan, and I'm wondering if there was a particular reason for that."

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:50.000
Coach:  Exactly.  And then connect it to the impact on student learning.  For example, you could say, "I'm concerned that skipping that activity might prevent students from developing this specific skill that's crucial for their understanding of the unit."

00:05:51.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Maria:  "I'm concerned that skipping that activity might prevent students from developing this specific skill..." Okay, I think I'm getting the hang of it.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:20.000
Coach:  You're doing great, Maria.  It sounds like you're really thinking through this carefully and considering the teacher's perspective.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:35.000
Maria:  This is really helpful, Sarah.  I feel much more prepared for this conversation now.  I was really dreading it, but now I feel like I have a good starting point.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:50.000
Coach:  You're welcome, Maria.  I'm confident you'll handle it well.  Just remember to be patient, listen to the teacher's perspective, and focus on finding solutions together.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:07:05.000
Maria:  I will.  Thanks for the reminder.  It's easy to get caught up in my own perspective and forget to really listen to what the teacher has to say.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Coach:  It's a common trap to fall into.  But it sounds like you're aware of that and committed to creating a space for open and honest communication.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Maria:  I am.  I want this to be a collaborative conversation where we can work together to ensure the best possible learning experiences for the students.  I think it's important for the teacher to feel like we're on the same team.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:50.000
Coach: That's a great mindset to have, Maria.  Creating that sense of partnership is essential for effective coaching.  And I think it will be helpful to reiterate the benefits of the new curriculum for the students during your conversation.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:08:05.000
Maria: That's an excellent idea. Sometimes I get so caught up in the details of implementation that I forget to remind teachers of the "why" behind the curriculum.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:20.000
Coach: Exactly. Reminding the teacher of the reasons why this new curriculum was adopted can help them see the value in implementing it fully.  What are some of the key benefits you could highlight?

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:35.000
